This positive ISM picture is, of course, somewhat at odds with factory orders which fell -1.0% m/m in May, after a +1.9% m/m bump in April.
At this point, ISM surveys are showing expansion in both manufacturing and non-manufacturing with encouraging stream of new orders for both.
ISM Manufacturing's extended dip into contraction territory (<50) was taken by many as sign of impending US recession. Not so.
ISM Manufacturing new orders for June were especially solid at 57.0, with export orders higher at 53.5. Firms cautious, employment was flat.
ISM Manufacturing for June rose to 53.2, up from 51.3 in May and beating expectations of 51.5. 4th straight month of (modest) expansion.
ISM Non-Manufacturing new orders reached 59.9, with new export orders rebounding 4 pts to 53.0. Employment also recovered 3 pts to 52.7.
ISM Non-Manufacturing Index for June surged to 56.5, up from 52.9 in May and surpassing expectations of 53.3. Solid expansion continues.
